OL,5,GMany will no doubt still be drawing
OL,6,Gbreath after the week's shenanigans at
OL,7,GWestminster.
OL,9,FEven those who would claim to
OL,10,Funderstand politics have been left
OL,11,Fastounded and mystified by twists which
OL,12,Fwould have seemed unthinkable until
OL,13,Frecently.
OL,15,FWhen events are unfolding so fast is it
OL,16,Fthe role of journalists to reflect that
OL,17,Fsense of disbelief? Or should they
OL,18,Fattempt to bring a degree of calm and
OL,19,Fcertainty?
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G1/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34502
SC,0002
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1667777620
OL,5,FThe opening of Wednesday's ITV News at
OL,6,FTen has gone viral and was shown by the
OL,7,FBBC on Have I Got News for You.
OL,9,FIt certainly reflected how many would
OL,10,Fhave been feeling  the events of
OL,11,FWednesday surrounding the vote on
OL,12,Ffracking and whether it was or was not
OL,13,Fan issue of confidence were a
OL,14,Fpantomime.
OL,16,FBut could you imagine a BBC News
OL,17,Fprogramme opening like that?
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G2/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34503
SC,0003
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1667777620
OL,5,FFrankly if Huw Edwards or Sophie
OL,6,FRayworth had done the same, there would
OL,7,Fhave been blood on the carpet somewhere
OL,8,Fin New Broadcasting House.
OL,10,FIt would have made the row when Emily
OL,11,FMaitlis suggested in a Newsnight intro
OL,12,Fthat it was clear Dominic Cummings
OL,13,Fbreached lockdown rules seem like a
OL,14,Fminor creative discussion.
OL,16,FYet after a link like Wednesday's on an
OL,17,FITV News programme, there is no row and
OL,18,Flittle public comment.
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G3/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34504
SC,0004
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1667777620
OL,5,FOf course some of the reason why nobody
OL,6,Fseemed to be that bothered about Tom
OL,7,FBradby's intro comes down to the
OL,8,Fultimate nature of the BBC's
OL,9,Frelationship with the government.
OL,11,FSome hostile MPs who like their names
OL,12,Fin print know they can call for funding
OL,13,Fcuts and even abolition.
OL,15,FThe BBC needs to keep its powder dry so
OL,16,Fit can protect its journalists when
OL,17,Fthey come under pressure for simply
OL,18,Fholding politicians to account or
OL,19,Fshining a light into dark corners.
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G4/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34505
SC,0005
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1667777620
OL,5,FIf the BBC had "provoked" some
OL,6,FConservatives with a Bradby-style
OL,7,Fintro, it could have served as a handy
OL,8,Fnewspaper and internet distraction from
OL,9,Fthe real matter in hand  namely a
OL,10,Fgovernment in complete chaos.
OL,12,FRentaquote MPs would be telling
OL,13,Fsympathetic newspapers how the BBC
OL,14,Fneeded muzzled or worse.
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G5/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34506
SC,0006
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1667777620
OL,5,FBut, much more importantly for the
OL,6,Fcorporation or any news editor, there
OL,7,Fis also the question of what viewers
OL,8,Fmight expect from the BBC: calmness,
OL,9,Fdoing nothing to undermine an
OL,10,Fimpression of complete impartiality and
OL,11,Fseeking clarity.
OL,13,FWhen the news is dramatic, there is
OL,14,Fcertainly no need to play anything
OL,15,Fother than a very straight bat.
OL,17,FSimply attempting to clearly explain
OL,18,Fand describe Wednesday's chaos  as BBC
OL,19,Fpolitical editor Chris Mason did
OL,20,Fexcellently  is in itself very
OL,21,Fpowerful.
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G6/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34507
SC,0007
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1667777620
OL,5,FIn a sense comparing the two bulletins
OL,6,Fon Wednesday is like contrasting rival
OL,7,Fnewspapers. The straight approach of a
OL,8,Fnewspaper of record like The Times with
OL,9,Fa punchy tabloid speaking for its
OL,10,Freaders.
OL,12,FNeither is in itself right or wrong but
OL,13,Fthe ratings seem to suggest the BBC
OL,14,Fapproach wins  even if many may have
OL,15,Fshared the disbelief projected in Tom
OL,16,FBradby's intro.
OL,18,FLast week we discussed whether the news
OL,19,Freally plays the same role on the two
OL,20,Fbig channels. Is it the centre of
OL,21,Fgravity or a PSB obligation?
OL,3,CWhy BBC News can't do Bradby-style
OL,4,Cintros
OL,22,                                  G7/10
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G
